  <h1>Section 142(1) notice: inquiry before assessment</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>5 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>A notice under Section 142(1) is an inquiry before assessment, used to require a taxpayer to file a return (if not filed), produce accounts and documents, or furnish information.</b> Non-compliance can lead to a best-judgment assessment under Section 144, a penalty under Section 272A and even prosecution.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">What the AO can require</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Consequences of non-compliance</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">How to respond</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Practical notes</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">What the AO can require</h2>
<p>Section 142(1) lets the Assessing Officer ask a taxpayer to:</p><ul><li>File a <b>return of income</b> where it has not been filed by the due date;</li><li>Produce <b>accounts and documents</b> (limited to three years before the previous year);</li><li>Furnish <b>information</b> on specified matters, including a statement of assets and liabilities.</li></ul><p>It is a pre-assessment fact-gathering tool and can precede a scrutiny under <a href="income-tax-notice-143-2-reply-guide.html">143(2)</a>.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Consequences of non-compliance</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Default</th><th>Consequence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Failure to comply</td><td>Best-judgment assessment under Section 144</td></tr><tr><td>Failure to respond</td><td>Penalty Rs.10,000 per default (Section 272A(1)(d))</td></tr><tr><td>Continued default</td><td>Possible prosecution under Section 276D</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

  <h2 id="s2">How to respond</h2>
<p>Respond on the e-filing portal within the time allowed, providing exactly what is asked, organised issue-wise. If the period to gather documents is short, request an adjournment through the portal. A complete, timely reply avoids a best-judgment assessment, which is usually adverse.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">Practical notes</h2>
<ul><li>The notice can be issued whether or not a return was filed.</li><li>Accounts older than three years before the previous year cannot be demanded.</li><li>Keep proof of submission (acknowledgement) for the record.</li><li>Audited financials, if applicable, should be ready &mdash; see <a href="form-3ca-3cb-3cd-difference.html">3CA/3CB/3CD</a>.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What can be asked under Section 142(1)?</summary><p>To file a return if not filed, to produce accounts and documents (up to three years before the previous year), or to furnish information including a statement of assets and liabilities.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What happens if I ignore a 142(1) notice?</summary><p>The AO can make a best-judgment assessment under Section 144, levy a penalty of Rs.10,000 per default under Section 272A, and in serious cases initiate prosecution.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Can a 142(1) notice be issued if I have not filed a return?</summary><p>Yes. One of its purposes is to require a return where it has not been filed by the due date.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>142(1) is a pre-assessment inquiry notice.</li><li>Can demand a return, accounts/documents, or information.</li><li>Non-compliance: best-judgment 144, Rs.10,000 penalty, prosecution risk.</li><li>Respond fully and on time via the portal.</li></ul>
  </div>

